node.text: Now here’s an absolute monster of a wave from @afonsobandagarra that is oh so worthy of recognition. Speaking of which, @nicvonrupp and his company @thebrusco have launched their #bruscochargerofthemonth comp, awarding the winner with a pack of surf goodies. “Our whole idea was to give credit and recognition to those underground chargers that constantly search for the best and heaviest waves in the Atlantic Ocean,” said Nic. “We want to inspire people to push their limits and there is no better example than these guys that put their lives on the line only for the pure love of surfing. This inspires me everyday and I believe it will also inspire the younger generations.” We couldn’t have said it better. Head over to the site for a full run down of this session and some insight from Afonso. Vid @vanlife_productions

node.text: Time for a 2-5 minute edit? Think most of us have these days. Every Friday, we'll be dropping one of our exclusive edits striaght to IG. First up, this session from deepest Cornwall in February of last year. The day before, the south west had been dripped by a blizzard, freezing over the roads and making travel damn near impossible. But a lucky crew managed to make the journey, hinderance free, and were greeted by a few barrels off this reefbreak. Featuring @alan_stokes @skindoggydog and many more, all shot by @biskit_bodyboarding you can find the full feature on the site, just search Cornwall in our shiny new nav bar.

node.text: UPDATE: We know Hurricane Larry will be a prolific swell producer for the US. And as he moves across the Atlantic, there could be a load of swell about to slam western Europe. Here's our swell chart showing Larry's latest track – boomeraing across the ocean and meeting with a system in the Bay of Biscay. Now, as of this moment, it looks like the remains of Larry could hit a bit later than originally forecast but also, with a more favourable wind. And though this is still a long way out, it's hard for us not to be excited about the potential for Europe, the UK and Ireland; with the UK experiencing one of the flattest summers in recent memory. Hopefully, this breaks the spell. Hit the link in bio for the full updated outlook. NOTE: swell chart shows Larry’s movements from tomorrow and into next Wednesday, Sept 15.

node.text: Explorer, sinologist, surf coach, @nikzanella has spent the last decade working in China, mapping the untapped coastline as well as at several levels of the national surf development project. However, few photographers do more than @benthouard to truly live up to iconic status. Hit the link in bio for a look at some of Ben’s masterworks.

node.text: Somewhere between Tijuana and Cabo San Lucas there’s a little corner of reef that holds sand in place—that turns lines into boxes, swell lines into slabs. It’s far from anywhere you’ve ever heard of and nowhere close to perfect, with a borderline impossible entry and a tricky doggy door exit, but there’s never anyone or anything there except coyotes and road runners, lizards and snakes, osprey and fish and dolphins and whales. Disconnecting in Baja; hit the link in bio. Pics by @tylerreid20

node.text: In 2019, big wave hellman @marcelolunaoficial went mysteriously silent, and no one heard much of anything out of him. As it turns out, Marcelo suffered a number of potentially career-ending injuries and has been holed up at home, rehabbing, healing, and chomping at the bit to get back out there. Then in May this year, when one of Brazil’s newly hyped monster slabs woke up for the first time in a few years, Marcelo made his comeback official, whipping a beast and shrugging off a severe beating as it were nothing. Hit the link in bio for the full story. Pics by @luisreis_photo
